content:
Keep producing no matter how hard it gets. As a creative worker who is a programmer &amp; software architect, a business owner, a startup advisor, a writer, an amateur content creator, and a lot more; they all revolve in the digital realm of &ldquo;you must produce something.&rdquo;
One thing I make sure I do everyday is I journal all my thoughts and significant events throughout the day. I always make sure I write for at least 15 minutes, every single day - even if I&rsquo;m not in the mood or it&rsquo;s a terrible day at work. I am committed to the process, not just seeking the outcome.
You will be measured by how much you get consistent on the things you are really passionate about. There is no such thing as waiting for motivation to strike, progress will just keep you going. Keep creating content, keep writing code, keep researching for the next startup unicorn, keep analysing business problems, only then you will find success.

Ideas are cheap. As a noun, it means nothing but a reference to something that could be great. It&rsquo;s just an abstract concept that doesn&rsquo;t have any tangible way for either you or others to experience.
In order for ideas to mean something, it needs to transition from a noun to a verb (action) because by only putting the work and process on to it, that&rsquo;s when value comes in. Only then, the idea becomes a product, a service, an outcome - and eventually turn in to business, profit, and purpose.
Ideas that stay as noun, in time will be regrets. &ldquo;I had that idea long ago&hellip;&rdquo; &ldquo;I thought about that&hellip;&rdquo; &ldquo;If only I did that&hellip;&rdquo; If you are really wedded to your idea, go do something about it. If not, move on&hellip;
